The '''Ellsworth–Whitmore Mountains''' ('''EWM''') is the innermost of the four or five [[allochthon]]ous [[terrane]]s, or tectonic blocks, that form [[West Antarctica]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Vaughan|Pankhurst|2008|loc=4.3 West Antarctica<!-- PDF pages 17–18 -->}}</ref> EWM was located in an [[embayment]] off [[Natal (region)|Natal]], [[South Africa]], before the break-up of [[Gondwana]] during which it was rotated 90° anticlockwise.<ref>{{Harvnb|Randall|Mac Niocaill|2004|loc=Abstract}}</ref> The EWM is named for the [[Ellsworth Mountains|Ellsworth]] and [[Whitmore Mountains|Whitmore]] mountain ranges.
The EWM was deformed during Gondwanan [[Late Permian]]–[[Late Jurassic]] [[Orogeny|orogenic events]] and is underlain by [[Grenville orogeny|Grenvillan]] crust that much older than the amalgamation of Gondwana. A 90° anticlockwise rotation of the EWM during the Gondwana break-up is supported by [[Paleomagnetism|palaeomagnetic]] data from several primary [[remanence]]s: the [[Late Cambrian]] [[Frazier Ridge|Frazier Ridge Formation]] and the [[Nash Hills]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Randall|Mac Niocaill|2004|loc=Introduction}}</ref>
The origin of the crustal blocks of West Antarctica and [[Zealandia]] remained enigmatic for decades largely because of their locations on the Pacific margin of Gondwana from where they were transported large distances.<ref>{{Harvnb|Grunov|Dalziel|Kent|1987|loc=West Antarctica and the Pacific Margin of Gondwanaland, pp. 161–162}}</ref> The EWM formed part of Gondwana's southern margin, Earth's longest and most long-lived [[active margin]]. Stretching from South America over South Africa, West Antarctica, [[Victoria Land]], New Zealand, and Eastern Australia, this margin was the location of the {{Convert|18000|km|abbr=on}}-long [[Terra Australis Orogen|Terra Australis orogeny]] that began during the Neoproterozoic break-up of [[Rodinia]] and culminated in the closure of the [[Adamastor Ocean|Adamastor]] and [[Mozambique Ocean|Mozambique]] oceans. During the Palaeozoic the central part of the southern margin, EWM together with the [[Sierra de la Ventana]] (Argentina) and the [[Cape Fold Belt]] (South Africa), was a [[passive margin]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Vaughan|Pankhurst|2008|loc=Abstract}}</ref>
