'''Eugênia Anna Santos''' (''Mãe Aninha, Oba Biyi''; [[Salvador, Bahia]], 13 July 1869 - Salvador, 3 January 1938) was a Brazilian [[Mãe-de-santo|Iyalorixá]]. She founded the [[candomblé]] [[Ilê Axé Opó Afonjá]] in Salvador, now considered a National Historic Landmark, and in [[Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name=palmares.gov.br>{{cite web|title=Personalidades Negras – Mãe Aninha|url=http://www.palmares.gov.br/?page_id=9854|publisher=Government of Brazil - Fundação Cultural Palmares|accessdate=13 December 2015|language=Portuguese}}</ref>

==Life==
Santos was born in 1869 to African parents of the [[Gurunsi]] nation.{{Sfn|Bay|Mann|2013|p=193}} She served as the chief female officer, known as ''prioreza'', of the Boa Morte sisterhood and Rosario brotherhood.{{sfn|Butler|1998|p=199}} In 1936, Santos was one of the founders of the Segundo Congresso Afro-Brasileiro.{{Sfn|Lopes|2015|p=207}}

==Legacy==
Santos is remembered for her great leadership qualities and strength.{{Sfn|Lopes|2015|p=207}} Author [[Kim Butler]] states that she "went further than any other priest in transforming the terreiro into an alternative, African world in the heart of Brazil", which "reflected ways in which the [[candomblé]] community was part of the larger Afro-Bahaian community".{{sfn|Butler|1998|p=199}} Darlene Clark Hine and [[Jacqueline McLeod]] credit her with moving the "candomblé out of the shadows by opening the doors of her terreiro to the international community".{{sfn|Hine|McLeod|1999|p=128}}

The Municipal School Eugenia Anna dos Santos was established in her name in 1978 to cater for nursery children aged 6 months to 5 years, and from 1986, for elementary children from 1st to 4th grade.{{Sfn|Wolhuter|Wet|2014|p=163}}

