{{italic title}}
'''''Going Nowhere Slowly''''' was a [[South Africa]]n travel-orientated television series, that attained [[Cult following|cult status]].<ref name="Taylor">{{Cite web|title=Stuart Taylor|publisher=HDS Entertainment|location=South Africa|url=http://www.hdsentertainment.co.za/stuart-taylor/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140105163859/http://www.hdsentertainment.co.za/stuart-taylor/|archivedate=5 January 2014|deadurl=no}}</ref> It follows a number of off beat travellers as they cruise across [[Southern Africa]], in an old American muscle car (usually a '1966s [[Chevrolet Impala]] known as the ''Chilli Pepper''). Along the way, the characters share their thoughts and experiences, many times ending up in sticky situations, such as running out of gas, falling out of moving cars and with the occasional injury they move through the least travelled spots to find the unique and crazy people who bring the magic to those destinations.

The show was completely unscripted. The travelers covered a total of 150 000&nbsp;km in 176 episodes through the following countries: South Africa, [[Namibia]], [[Zambia]], [[Swaziland]], [[Lesotho]], [[Botswana]], [[Zimbabwe]], [[Mozambique]], [[Malawi]], [[Tanzania]] and [[Madagascar]].

The show launched some of the actors into careers as comedians, the well remembered characters include [[Vivienne Vermaak]], [[Stuart Taylor (comedian)|Stuart Taylor]],<ref name="Taylor" /> [[Marc Lottering]], [[Ian Roberts (South African actor)|Ian Roberts]] and [[Fiona Coyne (presenter)|Fiona Coyne]].

The programme aired on [[SABC3]] from 2005 to 2009. After its initial season in 2005, it was renewed by the SABC for an additional 153 Episodes over six more Seasons, the series ended in 2009 having airing 176 episodes in seven Seasons . In the United States, it was syndicated for broadcast on [[The Africa Channel]]. A book for the second season, ''[[Red Car Diaries]]'', was published in 2006. This hit show syndicated across the planet, became the most successful travel documentary out of Africa.{{Citation needed|reason=use of a superlative|date=January 2014}}

During and after the last couple of seasons, the production company [[Big Blue Productions]] attempted to take the programme concept globally.{{Citation needed|reason=forecasting?|date=January 2014}}

