'''Japanese missions to Paekche''' represent an aspect of the international relations of mutual Paekche-Japanese contacts and communication.<ref>Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric. (2005). "Iki no Haktoko" in {{Google books|p2QnPijAEmEC|''Japan Encyclopedia'', pp. 379-380|page=379}}; n.b., Louis-Frédéric is pseudonym of Louis-Frédéric Nussbaum, ''see'' [http://dispatch.opac.ddb.de/DB=4.1/PPN?PPN=128842709 Deutsche Nationalbibliothek Authority File] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120524174828/http://dispatch.opac.ddb.de/DB=4.1/PPN?PPN=128842709 |date=2012-05-24 }}.</ref>  The bilateral exchanges were intermittent.

The unique nature of these bilateral diplomatic exchanges evolved from a conceptual framework developed by the Chinese.<ref>Kang, Etsuko H. (1997). ''Diplomacy and Ideology in Japanese-Korean Relations: from the Fifteenth to the Eighteenth Century,'' p. 81.</ref>

* 369-375 &mdash; Yamato Japan and Paekche maintain yearly exchanges of ambassadors.<ref>Hyung Il Pai. (2000). {{Google books|QxztLeLoVkQC|''Constructing "Korean" Origins: a Critical Review of Archaeology, Historiography, and Racial Myth in Korean State-Formation Theories,'' p. 234.|page=234}}</ref>

According to the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'', in the years 501-700 Japan sent 328 official missions to [[Baekje|Paekche]], 316 to [[Silla]], 146 to [[Goguryeo]], 193 to [[Mimana|Imna]] (Mimana), 20 to [[Gaya confederacy|Gaya]], 20 to [[Tamna]], and 5 to [[Samhan]] kingdoms.<ref>{{cite book |last=Park |first=Seong-rae |date=2005 |title=Science And Technology in Korean History |url= |location=Seoul |publisher=Jain Pub Co |page=39 |isbn= |access-date=18 March 2015}}</ref> Exchanges of embassies with the Korean kingdoms of Paekche and Silla were critical for informing the Japanese of cultural developments on the continent.<ref>Fuqua, Doug. [http://aboutjapan.japansociety.org/content.cfm/the_japanese_missions_to_tang_china_7th-9th_centuries  "The Japanese Missions to Tang China, 7th-9th Centuries," Japan Society (US). May 8, 2009; retrieved 2011-06-29]</ref>

