{{hatnote|This article is about the series of blockade batteries of 1798–1800. For other batteries in Sliema, see [[Lembi Battery]], [[Sliema Point Battery]], [[Cambridge Battery]] and [[Garden Battery]].}} {{Infobox military installation | name = Sliema Batteries | native_name = Batteriji ta' Tas-Sliema | partof = the [[Fortifications of Malta#French occupation (1798–1800)|French blockade batteries]] | location = [[Sliema]], [[Malta]] | image = | caption = | type = [[Artillery battery|Artillery batteries]] | coordinates = {{coord|35|54|39.1|N|14|30|19.3|E|type:landmark_region:MT|display=inline}} | built = {{circa}} 1798 | used = {{circa}} 1798–1800 | builder = [[Maltese people|Maltese]] insurgents | materials = [[Limestone]] | fate = Demolished | battles = [[Siege of Malta (1798–1800)]] | past_commanders = [[Vincenzo Borg]] }}
The '''Sliema Batteries''' ({{lang-mt|Batteriji ta' Tas-Sliema}}) were a series of [[artillery battery|artillery batteries]] in [[Sliema]], [[Malta]], that were built by Maltese insurgents during the [[Siege of Malta (1798–1800)|French blockade]] of 1798–1800. They were the first in [[Fortifications of Malta#French occupation (1798–1800)|a chain of batteries, redoubts and entrenchments]] encircling the French positions in [[Marsamxett Harbour|Marsamxett]] and the [[Grand Harbour]].
The batteries were built by [[Vincenzo Borg]]. The following batteries are known to have existed:<ref name=lloyd1811>{{cite book|title=The Appeals of the Nobility and People of Malta to the Justice, Public Faith, and Policy of the British Government, for the Fulfillment of the Conditions Upon which They Gave Up Their Island to the King, Namely Their Ancient Rights Under a Free Constitution|date=1811|publisher=R. Lloyd|location=[[London]]|page=32|url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=YitFAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA1-PA32&lpg=RA1-PA32#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> *'''Imrabat Battery''': This was armed with two or four mortars. It had an underground casemate (similar to the one at [[Għargħar Battery]]) and a gun crew shelter. It was surrounded by extensive walls and had a bastion. * '''Ischina Battery''': This was a small battery equipped with an 18-pounder, and was situated in a field known as ''ta' Xini''. It was possibly located at Fond Għadir, close to where [[Sliema Point Battery]] was later built. Vincenzo Borg often stood guard at this battery. *'''Sqaq Kappara Battery''': This battery overlooked and bombarded [[Fort Manoel]]. *Six walled positions along present day Main Street, including two batteries at Għar il-Lembi, armed with two and three guns. Other batteries known as ''tal-Blat'' and ''ta' Sbiese'' also existed.
The Sliema batteries still existed in 1811, but like the other French blockade fortifications, they were dismantled, possibly sometime after 1814. No traces of the batteries can be seen today.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Spiteri|first1=Stephen C.|title=Maltese ‘siege’ batteries of the blockade 1798–1800|journal=Arx – Online Journal of Military Architecture and Fortification|date=May 2008|issue=6|pages=41–43|url=http://www.militaryarchitecture.com/images/stories/Arx/arx6-2008.pdf|accessdate=30 March 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6hBuv3cHQ?url=http://www.militaryarchitecture.com/images/stories/Arx/arx6-2008.pdf|archivedate=1 May 2016|df=}}</ref>
